<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<worksheet xml:id="dc3-sample" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>DC-3 Sample Outcomes</title>
   <introduction>
    <p>For the quiz on this outcome you would be given 50 minutes to complete 4 problems. Here are samples 
      of the types of problems you will encounter:</p>
  </introduction>
  
  <page>
    <exercise>
        <statement><p>Let <m>z=3x^2+y^2</m>.Use the gradient to find the tangent plane at 
            the point <m>(1,-1,4)</m>.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>To find the tangent plane, first rewrite the equation as <m>f(x,y,z) = 3x^2 + y^2 - z = 0</m>, 
            then compute the gradient of <m>f</m> at the given point.</p></hint>
        <answer><p>The tangent plane is <m>6x - 2y - z = 4</m>.</p></answer>
        <solution><p>First, rewrite the equation as <m>f(x,y,z) = 3x^2 + y^2 - z = 0</m>.</p>
            <p>Compute the gradient of <m>f</m>:</p>
            <p><m>\nabla f = \left(6x, 2y, -1\right)</m></p>
            <p>Evaluate the gradient at the point <m>(1,-1, 4)</m>:</p>
            <p><m>\nabla f(1,-1,4) = \left(6, -2, -1\right)</m></p>
            <p>The equation of the tangent plane is:</p>
            <p><m>6(x-1) - 2(y+1) - 1(z-4) = 0</m></p>
            <p>Simplifying:</p>
            <p><m>6x - 6 - 2y - 2 - z + 4 = 0</m></p>
            <p><m>6x - 2y - z = 4</m></p></solution>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction><p>Given the function <m>f(x,y)=\sqrt{20-x^2-7y^2}</m></p></introduction>
        <task>
            <statement><p>Find the linearization of <m>f</m> at the point <m>(2,1)</m>.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>The linearization of <m>f</m> at <m>(a,b)</m> is given by <m>L(x,y) = f(a,b) + f_x(a,b)(x-a) + f_y(a,b)(y-b)</m>.</p></hint>
            <answer><p><m>L(x,y) = 3 + \frac{1}{3}(x-2) + \frac{7}{3}(y-1)</m></p></answer>
            <solution><p>First, find the partial derivatives of <m>f</m>:</p>
                <p><m>f_x = \frac{-x}{\sqrt{20-x^2-7y^2}}</m></p>
                <p><m>f_y = \frac{-7y}{\sqrt{20-x^2-7y^2}}</m></p>
                <p>Evaluate these at the point <m>(2,1)</m>:</p>
                <p><m>f(2,1) = \sqrt{20-4-7} = \sqrt{9} = 3</m></p>
                <p><m>f_x(2,1) = \frac{-2}{\sqrt{9}} = -\frac{2}{3}</m></p>
                <p><m>f_y(2,1) = \frac{-7}{\sqrt{9}} = -\frac{7}{3}</m></p>
                <p>The linearization is:</p>
                <p><m>L(x,y) = 3 - \frac{2}{3}(x-2) - \frac{7}{3}(y-1)</m></p></solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>Use the linearization to approximate <m>f(1.95,1.08)</m>.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>To find the linear approximation, substitute the values into the linearization formula.</p></hint>
            <answer><p><m>f(1.95,1.08) \approx 3 + \frac{1}{3}(1.95-2) + \frac{7}{3}(1.08-1) = 3 - \frac{1}{6} + \frac{7}{3}(0.08) = 3 - \frac{1}{6} + \frac{7}{3} \cdot 0.08</m></p></answer>
            <solution><p>Substitute <m>x = 1.95</m> and <m>y = 1.08</m> into the linearization:</p>
                <p><m>L(1.95,1.08) = 3 - \frac{2}{3}(1.95-2) - \frac{7}{3}(1.08-1)</m></p>
            <p>Simplifying:</p>
            <p><m>L(1.95,1.08) = 3 - \frac{2}{3}(-0.05) - \frac{7}{3}(0.08)</m></p>
            <p><m>L(1.95,1.08) = 3 + \frac{1}{30} - \frac{14}{75}</m></p>
            <p><m>L(1.95,1.08) = \frac{91}{30} + \frac{14}{75}</m></p>
            <p><m>L(1.95,1.08) = \frac{455}{150} - \frac{28}{150}</m></p>
            <p><m>L(1.95,1.08) = \frac{427}{150} \approx 2.8467</m></p></solution>
        </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <statement><p>Find the gradient of the function <m>f(x,y)=x^2\ln(y)</m>.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>To find the gradient, compute the partial derivatives with respect to each variable.</p></hint>
        <answer><p><m>\nabla f = \left\langle 2x\ln(y), \frac{x^2}{y} \right\rangle</m></p></answer>
        <solution><p>First we compute the partial derivatives:</p>
            <p><m>\frac{\partial f}{\partial x} = 2x\ln(y)</m></p>
            <p><m>\frac{\partial f}{\partial y} = \frac{x^2}{y}</m></p>
            <p>So, <m>\nabla f = \left\langle 2x\ln(y), \frac{x^2}{y} \right\rangle</m>.</p></solution>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <statement><p>Given <m>f(x,y)=e^{-x}\sin y</m>, find the directional derivative at the point 
            <m>(0, \frac{\pi}{3})</m> in the direction of the vector <m>\vec{u} = \langle 3, -2 \rangle</m>.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>To find the directional derivative, compute the gradient of <m>f</m> and then take the dot product with 
            the unit vector in the direction of <m>\vec{u}</m>.</p></hint>
        <answer><p></p></answer>
        <solution><p>First we compute the gradient:</p>
            <p><m>\nabla f = \left\langle \frac{\partial f}{\partial x}, \frac{\partial f}{\partial y} \right\rangle</m></p>
            <p><m>\frac{\partial f}{\partial x} = -e^{-x}\sin y</m></p>
            <p><m>\frac{\partial f}{\partial y} = e^{-x}\cos y</m></p>
            <p>So, <m>\nabla f = \left\langle -e^{-x}\sin y, e^{-x}\cos y \right\rangle</m>.</p>
            <p>Next, we evaluate the gradient at the point <m>(0, \frac{\pi}{3})</m>:</p>
            <p><m>\nabla f(0, \frac{\pi}{3}) = \left\langle -e^{0}\sin \frac{\pi}{3}, e^{0}\cos \frac{\pi}{3} \right\rangle</m></p> 
            <p><m>\nabla f(0, \frac{\pi}{3}) = \left\langle -\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}, \frac{1}{2} \right\rangle</m>.</p>
            <p>Now we find the unit vector in the direction of <m>\vec{u} = \langle 3, -2 \rangle</m>:</p>
            <p><m>\|\vec{u}\| = \sqrt{3^2 + (-2)^2} = \sqrt{13}</m></p>
            <p><m>\hat{u} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{13}}\langle 3, -2 \rangle = \left\langle \frac{3}{\sqrt{13}}, \frac{-2}{\sqrt{13}} \right\rangle</m></p>
            <p>Finally, we compute the directional derivative:</p>
            <p><m>D_{\hat{u}}f(0, \frac{\pi}{3}) = \nabla f(0, \frac{\pi}{3}) \cdot \hat{u} = \left\langle -\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}, \frac{1}{2} \right\rangle \cdot \left\langle \frac{3}{\sqrt{13}}, \frac{-2}{\sqrt{13}} \right\rangle</m></p>
            <p><m>D_{\hat{u}}f(0, \frac{\pi}{3}) = \frac{-3\sqrt{39}-2\sqrt{13}}{26}</m></p></solution>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction><p>Given the surface <m>x-z=4\arctan(yz)</m> and the point <m>(1+\pi, 1, 1)</m>:</p></introduction>
        <task>
            <statement><p>Find the equation of the tangent plane to the surface at the given point.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>To find the equation of the tangent plane, compute the gradient of the surface equation and evaluate it at the given point.</p></hint>
            <answer><p>tangent plane: <m>x - 2y - 3z + 2 = \pi - 4</m></p></answer>
            <solution><p> First we can rewrite the surface equation as <m>f(x,y,z) = x - z - 4\arctan(yz)</m>. Then we compute the gradient:</p>
                <p><m>\nabla F = \left\langle \frac{\partial F}{\partial x}, \frac{\partial F}{\partial y}, \frac{\partial F}{\partial z} \right\rangle</m></p>
                <p><m>\frac{\partial F}{\partial x} = 1</m></p>
                <p><m>\frac{\partial F}{\partial y} = -\frac{4z}{1 + (yz)^2}</m></p>
                <p><m>\frac{\partial F}{\partial z} = -1 - \frac{4y}{1 + (yz)^2}</m></p>
                <p>So, <m>\nabla F = \left\langle 1, -\frac{4z}{1 + (yz)^2}, -1 - \frac{4y}{1 + (yz)^2} \right\rangle</m>.</p>
                <p>Next, we evaluate the gradient at the point <m>(1+\pi, 1, 1)</m>:</p>
                <p><m>\nabla F(1+\pi, 1, 1) = \left\langle 1, -\frac{4}{1 + 1}, -1 - \frac{4}{1 + 1} \right\rangle</m></p>
                <p><m>\nabla F(1+\pi, 1, 1) = \left\langle 1, -2, -3 \right\rangle</m>.</p>
                <p>The equation of the tangent plane is:</p>
                <p><m>1(x-(1+\pi)) - 2(y-1) - 3(z-1) = 0</m></p>
                <p>Simplifying:</p>
                <p><m>x - (1+\pi) - 2(y-1) - 3(z-1) = 0</m></p>
                <p><m>x - (1+\pi) - 2y + 2 - 3z + 3 = 0</m></p>
                <p><m>x - 2y - 3z + 2 = \pi-4</m></p></solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>Find the equation of the normal line to the surface at the given point.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>To find the equation of the normal line, use the gradient of the surface equation evaluated at the given point as the direction vector.</p></hint>
            <answer><p>normal line: <m>\frac{x-(1+\pi)}{1} = \frac{y-1}{-2} = \frac{z-1}{-3}</m></p></answer>
            <solution><p>Since the gradient at the given point is <m>\nabla F(1+\pi, 1, 1) = \left\langle 1, -2, -3 \right\rangle</m>, the equation of the normal line is:</p>
                <p><m>\frac{x-(1+\pi)}{1} = \frac{y-1}{-2} = \frac{z-1}{-3}</m></p></solution>
        </task>
    </exercise>
    </page>
</worksheet>